{
  "no_corrections_needed": false,
  "corrections": [
    {
      "type": "reverse",
      "source": "breakeven_10y",
      "target": "real_10y",
      "justification": "The Fisher decomposition defines: nominal_yield = real_10y + breakeven_10y. In the TIPS market, the nominal 10-year Treasury yield and the TIPS (real) yield are both directly traded/priced instruments, and breakeven inflation is *derived* as their spread (nominal minus real). Causally, the real yield and the nominal yield are the primary market quantities; breakeven is computed from them. However, among real_10y and breakeven_10y specifically, Fed policy and inflation expectations are the upstream drivers that move both. The edge as currently drawn (breakeven_10y -> real_10y) implies inflation expectations mechanically determine the real yield, which inverts the more defensible direction: changes in real yields (driven by monetary policy and growth expectations) shift the TIPS yield, and breakeven is derived residually. The more defensible causal direction is real_10y <- upstream drivers, and breakeven_10y <- upstream drivers, with no direct edge between them — but if one must exist, real_10y -> breakeven_10y (or removal) is preferable to the current reverse. Reversing to real_10y -> breakeven_10y is the correction."
    },
    {
      "type": "remove",
      "source": "ig_spread",
      "target": "vix",
      "justification": "Both IG credit spreads and VIX are endogenous responses to common upstream drivers of financial stress (economic contraction, policy uncertainty, geopolitical shocks) rather than one causing the other. While they are correlated, the causal mechanism from credit spreads to equity implied volatility is weak compared to the shared-cause explanation; VIX is driven by equity option demand and reflects forward equity uncertainty, not directly by corporate bond spreads. This edge is better explained as a spurious co-movement from shared upstream causes (epu, gpr, oecd_cli, unemployment) rather than a genuine causal relationship."
    },
    {
      "type": "remove",
      "source": "vix",
      "target": "sp500_ret",
      "justification": "VIX is derived from S&P 500 option prices and therefore contemporaneously reflects expected future equity volatility; it does not causally drive S&P 500 returns within the same period in a structural sense. The relationship runs the other way at monthly frequency: large negative equity returns cause VIX to spike (the leverage/volatility-feedback effect). The current edge vix -> sp500_ret is likely a false positive arising from their strong contemporaneous correlation; the more defensible causal direction is sp500_ret -> vix (i.e., equity selloffs drive fear index up), not the reverse."
    },
    {
      "type": "add",
      "source": "sp500_ret",
      "target": "vix",
      "justification": "At monthly frequency, negative S&P 500 returns are a primary driver of VIX spikes through the leverage effect and increased demand for put options as hedges. This well-documented causal mechanism (equity drawdowns -> elevated implied volatility) is missing from the graph. The existing edge vix -> sp500_ret should be replaced with this reverse direction to correctly capture the leverage/volatility-feedback channel."
    },
    {
      "type": "remove",
      "source": "ig_spread",
      "target": "sp500_ret",
      "justification": "IG credit spreads and S&P 500 returns are both driven by common upstream factors (financial stress, recession risk, policy uncertainty) rather than credit spreads directly causing equity returns at monthly frequency. While they are correlated, the structural causal mechanism from IG OAS to S&P 500 monthly returns is weak; both are better modeled as co-effects of shared upstream causes such as oecd_cli, epu, and unemployment, making this edge more likely a false positive."
    },
    {
      "type": "remove",
      "source": "fed_funds",
      "target": "gold_price",
      "justification": "The causal mechanism from Fed Funds to gold is already fully mediated by real_10y (which captures the real opportunity cost) and breakeven_10y (which captures inflation expectations). Fed Funds influences gold through its effect on the yield curve and real rates, not directly. Including a direct edge from fed_funds to gold_price alongside the mediated paths through real_10y and breakeven_10y constitutes over-specification and likely represents a false positive direct edge when the paths through interest rate variables adequately capture the monetary policy transmission channel."
    },
    {
      "type": "remove",
      "source": "unemployment",
      "target": "gold_price",
      "justification": "The causal effect of unemployment on gold price is fully mediated through existing paths: unemployment -> fed_funds -> real_10y/breakeven_10y -> gold_price, and unemployment -> cpi_yoy -> gold_price, and unemployment -> ig_spread -> gold_price, and unemployment -> mich_pessim -> gold_price. A direct edge from unemployment to gold_price bypasses these well-defined mechanisms and likely constitutes a false positive over-specification; the mechanisms are all captured through intermediate variables already in the graph."
    }
  ]
}
